{"key":"processedPost-10082263","value":{"id":10082263,"first":10081356,"last":10082757,"when":1238544603,"utime":"04/01/09 03:10 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />but the agar plates (the lids especially) have a lot of moisture drops from the pressure cooker. Is there any way to prevent condensation build up as the plates cool? </blockquote><br />You don't cook the agar in the petri dishes.&nbsp; You sterilize the agar in a separate bottle and pour the dishes after it's nearly cool.&nbsp; This prevents excessive condensation.&nbsp; Here's a <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Agar-Petri-Dishes\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">writeup and video</a> of how I do it.<br />If the tissue doesn't take, you're probably trying to clone a full size mushroom.&nbsp; Always clone a rapidly growing fruit, preferably a pin.&nbsp; Once the fruit quits growing, it's done.<br />It doesn't matter where you grab your tissue, as long as it's fresh tissue that was never exposed to the air until your tore the mushroom in half.<br />RR","title":"Re: Having trouble cloning on agar..."}}